<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-06T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-06T15:00:00-05:00" n="56" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d56">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/543: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Castleman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-06T14:00:00-06:00">September 6, 1937—2
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 5:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>96. For Duggan.<note n="24" xml:id="d56fn24">Laurence Duggan, Chief
                                    of the Division of the American Republics.</note> Cramp and I
                                have arranged by telephone that the Foreign Offices of Nicaragua and
                                Honduras are to talk by telephone <pb facs="0076" n="66" xml:id="pg_66"/> at 4 this afternoon to arrange simultaneous
                                presentation of assurances that troops will not be moved, covering
                                the following points: hour of presentations, form and extent of
                                assurances, appropriate publicity.</p>
                            <p>We will telegraph after the interview.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Castleman</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>